#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:113
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Configuring GnuPG.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:117
msgid ""
"As shown in the script below, the default settings can be applied for most "
"of the required parameters. Only the values for the key owner have to be "
"entered correctly, with a proper password specified for the key."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:122
msgid ""
"Now OTRS has to be made ready to use PGP. From the Admin console, open the "
"SysConfig interface and search for \"PGP\". Select the sub group Crypt::PGP "
"from the search results."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:126
msgid ""
"In the screen for the PGP settings, PGP should be activated for OTRS (first "
"option). Also, the path to the gpg program should be set and checked."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:130
msgid ""
"The next config setting (PGP::Options) may also require changing. Via this "
"config setting, the parameters that are used for every execution of gpg by "
"the 'otrs' user can be specified. In particular, the directory of the config "
"files for GnuPG of the 'otrs' user is important. In the example "
"<filename>/opt/otrs/.gnupg</filename> is used. This directory was created "
"earlier during the PGP configuration."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:134
msgid ""
"Via the next config option (PGP::Key::Password) it is possible to specify "
"the pairs of key IDs and their passwords for own private keys. Because "
"communication partners from outside write to the ticket system with their "
"messages encrypted with your public key, OTRS can decrypt these messages "
"with the ID/passwords specified here."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:138
msgid ""
"How to get the id of your own private key? The ID of your own private key is "
"already shown during the key generation (see step 1 from above). It is also "
"possible to get the ID if the command specified in the following script is "
"executed as user 'otrs':"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para><screen>
#: en/pgp.xml:143
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    linux:~# su otrs\n"
"    linux:/root$ cd\n"
"    linux:~$ pwd\n"
"    /opt/otrs\n"
"    linux:~$ gpg --list-keys\n"
"    /opt/otrs/.gnupg/pubring.gpg\n"
"    ----------------------------\n"
"    pub   1024D/7245A970 2006-02-03\n"
"    uid                  Ticket System (Private pgp key for ticket system "
"with\n"
"    address support@example.com) &lt;support@example.com&gt;\n"
"    sub   2048g/52B97069 2006-02-03\n"
"\n"
"    linux:~$\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:160
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Getting the ID of your own private key.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:164
msgid ""
"The ID of the private key can be found in the line that starts with "
"\"sub\". It is a hexadecimal string that is eight characters long, in the "
"example above it is \"52B97069\". The password you have to specify for this "
"key in the ticket system is the same that was given during key generation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:168
msgid ""
"After this data is inserted, the \"Update\" button can be used to save the "
"settings. OTRS is ready to receive and decrypt encoded messages now."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:173
msgid ""
"Finally, import a customer's public key. This ensures that encrypted "
"messages can be sent out to this customer. There are two ways to import a "
"public key of a customer."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:177
msgid ""
"The first way is to specify the public key of a customer in the customer "
"management interface."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:181
msgid ""
"The second way is to specify the key via the PGP settings, reachable from "
"the Admin page. On the right section of this screen, all already imported "
"public keys of customers are displayed. After PGP has been activated and "
"configured for OTRS, your own public key should also be listed there. In the "
"left area of the PGP setting screen it is possible to search for keys. Also, "
"a new public key can be uploaded into the system from a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/pgp.xml:185
msgid ""
"The files with the public key that need to be imported into OTRS have to be "
"GnuPGP compatible key files. In most cases, the key stored in a file is an "
"\"ASCII armored key\". OTRS can deal with this format."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><title>
#: en/smime.xml:7
msgid "S/MIME"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para>
#: en/smime.xml:10
msgid ""
"At first glance, encryption with S/MIME seems a little more complicated than "
"with PGP. First, you have to establish a Certification Authority (CA) for "
"the OTRS system, following which the procedures are very much like those "
"needed with PGP: configure OTRS, install your own certificate, import other "
"public certificates as needed, etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para>
#: en/smime.xml:14
msgid ""
"The S/MIME configuration is conducted outside the OTRS web interface for the "
"most part, and should be carried out in a shell by the 'otrs' user. The MIME "
"configuration under Linux is based on SSL (OpenSSL). Therefore, check first "
"of all whether the OpenSSL package is installed on your system. The OpenSSL "
"package includes a script called CA.pl, with which the most important steps "
"of certificate creation can be performed. To simplify the procedure, find "
"out where in the filesystem the CA.pl script is stored and enter the "
"location temporarily into the PATH variable of the shell (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para><screen>
#: en/smime.xml:19
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"otrs@linux:~&gt; rpm -ql openssl | grep CA\n"
"/usr/share/ssl/misc/CA.pl\n"
"otrs@linux:~&gt; export PATH=$PATH:/usr/share/ssl/misc\n"
"otrs@linux:~&gt; which CA.pl\n"
"/usr/share/ssl/misc/CA.pl\n"
"otrs@linux:~&gt; mkdir tmp; cd tmp\n"
"otrs@linux:~/tmp&gt;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para>
#: en/smime.xml:30
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Configuring S/MIME.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para>
#: en/smime.xml:34
msgid ""
"The script above shows that a new temporary directory ~/tmp has been "
"created, in which the certificate is to be generated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><para>
#: en/smime.xml:38
msgid ""
"To create a certificate, perform the following operations in the command "
"line (we assume that the OTRS administrator has to create a SSL certificate "
"for test and learning purposes. In case you already have a certified SSL "
"certificate for the encryption, use it and skip these steps):"
msgstr ""

